<LEADPARA>  ACCORDING to legend, Buffalo chicken wings took flight in 1964 at the Anchor
Bar in Buffalo, N.Y. At that time, Buffalo's pre-eminent bar food was roast
beef on weck, thinly sliced meat wrapped in thin gravy on a kimmelweck roll, a
kaiser roll topped with coarse salt and caraway seeds.;    One evening, Anchor
Bar co-owner Teressa Bellissimowas asked by her son Dom to throw together some
freebie eats for a bunch of regulars who were hungry after spending a lot of
money at the bar.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  'REAL' WINGS NEED CELERY AND BLUE CHEESE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related articles pages 1C and 6C  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Not wanting to use expensive ingredients but endeavoring to provide
something substantial, Teressa cut off the wings from a few handy chickens.
Then she removed the bony tips and cut the remainder in half at the joint.
(The meatier part of the wing has become known as a drumette for obvious
reasons. No name has been given to the other part, which looks like an
oversize safety pin covered with skin.);    Teressa deep-fried the wings and
tossed them with some hot sauce. She served them with celery sticks taken from
an antipasto platter and some blue cheese dressing, normally reserved for
salads. Buffalo chicken wings were born.;    Most great bar foods have staunch
advocates who insist they can only be made one way. In the case of Buffalo
chicken wings, purists insist on the following:;    (check) Wings should never
be breaded or floured.;    (check) Deep frying is the only accepted cooking
method. The choice of fat is up to you. If you want to make some concession to
health, use canola oil.;    (check) The choice of hot sauce is crucial. The
original hot sauce was Frank's Louisiana Red Hot Sauce. Durkee's has a hot
sauce that it claims is formulated from Frank's original recipe. I tested
Durkee's against Crystal Louisiana Hot Sauce. I preferred Durkee's because it
had a creamier texture and a more appealing color (some wings have a putrid,
pale orange color). The level of heat and spice was about the same.;
(check) It ain't Buffalo wings unless it has blue cheese dressing and celery
sticks. Yes, these accompaniments came about by accident, but so did the
elements in chicken Marengo. Some people try to cheat with ranch-style
dressing instead of blue cheese. Sorry, no dice.;    BUFFALO CHICKEN WINGS;
20 chicken wings;   Oil for deep frying;  4 tablespoons butter;  5 tablespoons
Durkee's Louisiana Hot Sauce;  1 tablespoon white vinegar;   Remove the tips
from the wings. Discard or save for stock. Cut the rest in half at the joint.
Dry thoroughly on paper towels.;    Put oil in a large skillet, saucepot or
fryer to a depth of 2 inches. Heat to a temperature of 350 degrees or until
hot but not smoking. Add as many wings as possible in one layer so that they
do not crowd. Fry 7 minutes, turning periodically to cook evenly. Drain on
paper towels. Repeat until all the wings are cooked. Cool. (You can cook the
dish all the way at this point by adding 2 minutes to the cooking time.);
Make sauce by melting butter with hot sauce and vinegar. When ready to serve
wings, reheat oil and cook wings 2 minutes until just crisped and heated
through. Drain again on paper towels. When all the wings are cooked, put them
in a large bowl. Pour sauce over them and toss thoroughly. Serve on a platter
with excess sauce poured over. Serve with celery sticks and blue cheese
dressing.  </TEXT>
