<HEAD>`Beefalo' Roam onto Highway, Cause Five Accidents</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to CORRECT that animals are part-buffalo,
part-cattle known as `beefalo.' Picks up 9th graf pvs, ``What
they're...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A herd of a relative of the buffalo known as the
beefalo roamed onto the Florida Turnpike early Sunday, causing five
accidents and costing the lives of seven of the huge animals,
police said. One motorist was slightly injured.
   ``About 75 to 100 buffalo broke through a hole in the fence on
the Florida Turnpike Extension'' in northwest Dade County about
12:30 a.m., said Florida Highway Patrol Sgt. Alvis Chinn.
   The animals _ part buffalo, part beef cattle _ were part of a
400-head herd kept on a ranch near the turnpike extension, which
borders the Everglades northwest of Miami.
   Five of the beefalo died instantly or nearly so after they
collided with vehicles on the highway, Chinn said. ``I believe that
two other buffalo had to be killed later by the humane society,''
he said.
   The animals caused an estimated $18,000 to $20,000 damage
overall to the cars that collided with them, he said.
   The injured motorist was treated at a local hospital and
released, Chinn said.
   State troopers, animal-control officers, passers-by and workers
from the ranch herded the rest of the animals back home.
   Investigators believe the beefalo left their pasture after horse
thieves cut the fence.
   ``What they're doing apparently is stealing the horses in the
early morning hours, and they're leaving without fixing the
fence,'' Chinn said.
   Police have recorded 29 horse thefts in the area, with seven
horses stolen in the last two weeks, Chinn said.
   Dr. Arnie Oper, owner of the ranch, did not return messages left
on his answering machines Sunday.
   Oper recently made the news by offering any would-be Buffalo
Bills a chance to hunt and kill his animals for $3,500 each _ with
the hunter getting to keep the meat and the hide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

