<LEADPARA>  Like Indians over the centuries, Henry Beaver feels he possesses a spiritual
connection with buffalo. He also hunts them to feed his family.;    "I always
have buffalo in the fridge," Beaver said.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  General News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CANADA'S WAR OVER THE BUFFALO  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     So Beaver, other natives in this subarctic wilderness and environmentalists
around the world are coming to the defense of the 3,500 buffalo in and around
Wood Buffalo National Park -- the largest free-roaming herd in the world.;
The bison have been threatened with mass destruction by the Canadian
government because many of them are afflicted with tuberculosis and
brucellosis, diseases that could scar the lungs of cattle or cause them to
abort. The disease is transmitted by physical contact and inhalation.;    As
cattle and buffalo habitats slowly converge, the Canadian beef industry has
been calling for the elimination of the diseased bison, and the federal
Agriculture Department agrees. Under the plan, the bison herd would be
exterminated, then slowly rebuilt with disease-free beasts.;    However, a
recent outcry forced the government to back off from its extermination plan.
Instead, federal officials appointed a 19-member board, which has begun
meeting to devise an alternate plan.;    The Indians fear the killing of the
bison because they are a source of food and are a cultural icon. They and
others also noted the irony of the government's original plan. Wood Buffalo
Park was established in the 1920s as a haven for the bison, which numbered 60
million in North America before invaders hunted them down to mere thousands.;
  Reaching a consensus on the bison's future is sure to be difficult. The
natives, according to Beaver, favor testing the buffalo, segregating the
diseased animals and regenerating the herd with the healthy ones.;    "It's
ecologically, environmentally and economically the best way," Beaver said.;
The beef industry thinks there's no other way but to eliminate the diseased
herd, according to Jim Graham, president of the Canadian Cattlemen's
Association. That is how ranchers deal with partly tainted cattle herds.;
"We believe in disease eradication," said Graham. "If it is necessary to
depopulate, then we depopulate. That would apply to all species.";    Either
plan will be costly. Cost of the mass-slaughter option was estimated at $17.8
million. Beaver said the natives' plan might cost $26.7 million to $71.2
million.;    The diseases were introduced in the 1920s, when nearly 7,000
buffalo from central Alberta were brought north.;    Henry Beaver said he
shoots two buffalo a year to get meat for his wife and five children. He wants
the buffalo preserved:;    "It is food on our table, but it has a spiritual
value, too, because it shows our relationship with the earth. We know that our
people will get stronger spiritually if we help the buffalo."  </TEXT>
