<LEADPARA>  The National Park Service said Wednesday that it will honor, reluctantly, its
commitment to help kill bison that wander out of Yellowstone National Park and
threaten Montana cattle with disease.;    "We've agreed to do this -- not
because we want to, but because it's the correct thing to do given the
circumstances," said Joe Alston, Yellowstone's assistant superintendent.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  RANGERS TO KILL WANDERING BISON
MONTANA FEARS SPREAD OF DISEASE TO CATTLE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     His comment followed a federal judge's ruling Tuesday allowing the state of
Montana to proceed with a plan that calls for Yellowstone park rangers to join
state game wardens and citizen hunters in shooting bison outside Yellowstone.;
   Half of the estimated 3,000 bison in Yellowstone are believed to be
infected with brucellosis, a disease that causes domestic cattle to lose their
calves.;    Ron Aasheim of the Montana Department of Fish, Wildlife and Parks
said Wednesday there were no immediate plans to begin shooting bison.;
Animal-rights activists gathered at the town of West Yellowstone to protest
the hunt. Yellowstone officials said there are fewer than a half-dozen buffalo
grazing back and forth across the park boundary that might be targets.;    The
national Fund for Animals went to federal court seeking an injunction to stop
the killing.;    U.S. District Judge Charles Lovell denied that request late
Tuesday, saying it "would not be in the public interest given the serious
threat of brucellosis, the large number of excess bison, and the lack of
feasible alternatives to control bison migrating out of the park.";
"Montana has an absolute right under its police powers, in protecting the
health, safety and welfare of its inhabitants, to remove by reasonable means
possibly infected trespassing federal bison which migrate into Montana," the
judge said.;    Alston said the plan is a "legitimate approach to the problem"
while efforts continue to devise long-term solutions, including a joint
federal-state environmental impact statement that is at least a year away.;
Last summer, Gov. Stan Stephens accepted Yellowstone Superintendent Robert
Barbee's offer of rangers to assist Montana wardens in killing wayward bison.;
   Park rangers once culled herds by killing surplus animals, but have not
done so since 1966.;    Lovell said "the anomaly of management through
non-management" has resulted in a surplus of 600 bison over the park's
capacity.;    In 1988-'89, Montana hunters and wardens killed 569 bison north
of the park boundary. Only four were killed the following winter when
animal-rights activists disrupted the hunts. So far this winter, 11 bulls have
been killed near West Yellowstone.  </TEXT>
