<TEXT>     That time is past. But the respect American Indians feel for the buffalo
lives on.;    For those attending the traditional Indian feast and silent art
auction recently at Mother Olson's Inn in San Jose, the entree -- roasted
buffalo in garlic sauce -- was as special as the occasion.;    The dinner, a
benefit for the South Bay Quincentennial Indigenous Council, was prepared by
Lee A. Sprague, the founder of Menomin Caterers in Oakland (today's Four-Star
chef). Menomin means "wild rice" in the Indian language of Anishanabe.;    The
menu featured fruited wild rice, blue cornmeal muffins and peppermint tea.;
A Potawatomi-Ottawa and Ojibwe Indian with almost waist-length braids, Sprague
held up a food-laden plate as he addressed the crowd. "This first plate," he
said, "is for Grandfather's spirit, which is here with us tonight.";
Sprague has savored the rich flavor of buffalo all his life. "It has a
nourishing quality about it," he says.;    That rich flavor was a hit at the
Indian feast, where diners listened to guitarist Ronnie Padilla and marveled
over their first taste of buffalo.;    "It's sweet," said Consuelo Underwood,
an art professor at San Jose State University and one of the auction's
exhibiting artists. Maria Luisa Alaniz, a social scientist, called it "lean
and tender.";    The tenderness and sweetness, Sprague says, come from
roasting it at low temperatures.;    For Betty Glass, the roast buffalo dinner
brought back memories from 45 years ago of her then-104-year-old grandmother,
an American Indian from the Ohio area.;    "She was an Indian princess,"
recalled Glass, 71. "She married an Irish-English trapper. Being here tonight
makes me proud of my Indian heritage.";    The buffalo was once an important
food source, playing a significant role in the everyday life of the Indians,
said the council's George Martin, a Thlinget Indian.;    "Our lives were tied
to the buffalo's life. But the United States government allowed the buffalo to
be hunted for sport," Sprague said. "We became dependent on food arranged
around the reservation system. Our lives changed.";    Though the buffalo
faced near extinction, today its numbers are growing. There are more than
90,000 buffalo nationwide, according to Kim Dawling of the National Buffalo
Association in South Dakota.;    The growing consumer demand for
low-cholesterol, lean meat may increase the popularity of buffalo meat,
Sprague predicts.;    Buffalo meat contains 50 percent fewer calories than
beef, as well as 30 percent more protein, 25 percent less cholesterol -- and a
quarter of the fat.;    "My frame of reference," Sprague says, "is that beef
tastes like buffalo -- only not as good.";    Buffalo meat also links American
Indians with their ancestral and historical legacy.;    As a caterer and an
Indian, Sprague says, "I feel a strong responsibility to use the foods that
came from our people. These foods, such as the buffalo meat, make me feel
connected to my ancestors.";    This concern with maintaining ancestral links
underlies the meaning behind the Quincentennial Indigenous Council. It was
established as a response to the upcoming 500th anniversary of Columbus' 1492
arrival in the Americas to voice an alternative quincentennial view: that
Columbus' arrival began an invasion that led to the genocide of the
continents' indigenous peoples.;    "To me," Sprague says, "1492 represents
the changes our people experienced during and after Columbus' arrival. Our
people didn't know of the changes to come. We welcomed him; we fed him; we
introduced new foods to him.;    "When I see tomatoes in Italian dishes or the
chocolate in candy bars -- that people may think originated in Switzerland --
I think of all of the foods that came from the Americas.;    "Buffalo is my
soul food," Sprague says. "Knowing that my grandfathers ate buffalo and wild
rice makes me feel closer to them.";     Where to buy buffalo;  Lee Sprague,
owner of Menomin Caterers in Oakland, gets his buffalo meat from the Durham
Meat Co., 1160 Sunol St., San Jose, (408) 298-6404, which owns 4,000 head at
its 60,000-acre ranch in Wyoming. (Durham is developing a retail line -- from
ground patties to steaks and roasts -- for frozen-foods sections.);    Other
suppliers and distributors:;    (box) Bread of Life, 1690 S. Bascom Ave.,
Campbell; (408) 371-5000.;    (box) Schaub's, Stanford Shopping Center; (415)
325-6328.;    (box)  Durham Night Bird, 358-A Shaw Road, South San Francisco;
(415) 737-5879;    Cooking tips;  Buffalo can be substituted in most beef
recipes, but it must be cooked at lower temperatures. Cook to rare or medium
for best results. Buffalo cooks faster than beef. Here are some cooking tips:;
   (box)  For roasting a 3- to 4-pound buffalo roast, Sprague gives these
directions: Rub it with crushed garlic and corn oil, then sprinkle it with
pepper and salt. Wrap foil around the bottom of the roast and place a bay leaf
inside the foil to season the drippings.;    Roast uncovered at 325 degrees.
During the first hour, baste with the drippings several times. Then turn the
roast over so it browns on both sides, and cover it completely with foil for
another half-hour or until a meat thermometer registers an internal
temperature of 130 to 140 degrees.;    To serve, make a gravy from the
drippings with added water and vegetable bouillon.;    (box)  For crock-pot
cooking: Use the lowest temperature and let it cook all day.;    (box)  For
broiling: Move the broiler rack as far as possible from the heat and shorten
cooking time.;    (box)  For grilling: Never put buffalo in the flame. Keep
the temperature low or let the coals die down. Marinate and then baste
frequently.;    (box)  For the microwave: Brown steaks quickly in frying pan,
then place in microwave at high for 24-40 seconds until medium or rare.;
(box)  For stir-frying: Cut into small strips or cubes and fry with a very
small amount of olive oil (just enough to coat the pan). Keep the heat down.;
