domestic livestock. The disease causes cattle to abort their young.;    Wayne
Pacelle, national director of the 200,000-member group, said the appeal was
filed Tuesday morning in San Francisco.;    Legality questioned;  "We don't
just want a hearing. We want our legal arguments to be heard," Pacelle said.;
  The fund contends that Lovell's decision failed to focus on legal issues.;
 "The court's pro-hunting opinions and its concern for the reputation of
Montana are irrelevant to this case," he said. "The salient legal issue is the
failure of the state of Montana and the (National) Park Service to obey the
standards of federal and state law.";    The fund contends that Montana's
bison-killing plan violates both the National Environmental Policy Act and the
Montana Environmental Policy Act.;    Long-range study;  The acts forbid
"significant interim action" on the bison while a long-range plan is being
prepared, the fund argues.;    Montana, the Park Service and the U.S. Forest
Service are conducting a long-range study of the bison migration problem that
will not be completed for at least a year, officials say.;    The interim
plan, approved early this month, allows for the shooting of all bison that
cross the park border into Montana.  </TEXT>
